Topic: Multilevel Modeling

Priscila Lopez-Beltran Forcada, Ph.D.

Updated on July, 2023

In this workshop, we will learn the basics of multilevel modeling. I suggest to go over the previous topic, *Linear Regression”, before moving on to the material below.


We will use the same materials as in the previous topic, but I will repeat the design of the experiment at hand so you can understand the data better.


Let’s look at some real data from López-Beltrán et al., (2021)

We have a 2x2 repeated measures experiment where we want to test if there are differences in the processing of active and passive sentences depending on information structure. There is strong evidence that passive sentences are more costly to process than their active counterparts (i.e., higher Reading Times, RTs). However, we hypothesize that the cost of processing passive sentences might be alleviated when they are presented with a Given-New information structure pattern that is congruent with their discourse context, as shown below:

The following predictions are made:

  1. Actives will be read faster than passives
  2. Given-New (Congruent) will be read faster than New-Given (Incongruent)
  3. Passive New-Given will be the most costly condition (slowest RTs)

In addition,there might be a positive correlation between proficiency (as indexed by vocabulary size) and RTs.
Let’s visualize it, does the graph seem to meet the predictions?

Multilevel Modeling

The first crucial concept to understand is that these models are used when we have hierarchical, also called nested, data. These data have levels, hence multilevel, that group the data together. See the example below:



Multilevel models have a series of benefits that make them superior to other methods:

1. Heterogeneity of slopes: unlike linear regression or ANOVA, multilevel models are especially designed to model variability in regression slopes, homogeneity of variance is not assumed.

2. Assumption of independence: multilevel models deal with nested data and, as such, do not assume that data points are necessarily independent of each other. In fact, they are designed to model this dependency.

3. Missing data: they can handle missing data really well, unlike regression or ANOVA.

4. Variance: a single analysis including random effects of participant and item can replace the usual separate ANOVAs by participant and by item.


Fixed vs. Random

1. Coefficients: Intercepts and Slopes

  • Random intercepts: the relationship between x-y (predictor-outcome) is the same (tilt doesn’t change), just located at different geometric space.
    In a nutshell:
    Random intercepts model the variance between subjects and between items in the mean of the dependent variable. For example, some participants may generally read sentences faster than others, and thus have lower intercepts; or some items may be read more slowly than others, and thus have higher intercepts.

  • Random slopes: the relationship between x-y is different (tilt changes), but located at the same geometric space.
    In a nutshell:
    Random slopes model the variance between subjects and between items for all main effects and interactions. For example, some participants may read active sentences much faster than the passive sentences, having a more pronounced tilt to their slopes; while another subset of participants may show this same trend but with a smaller difference, have a less pronounced tilt.

  • Random intercepts and slopes: the relationship between x-y varies by shape and location. This is the most realistic model of the data.



2. Variables

The distinction between fixed and random variables is be crucial when considering which predictors can de included in our random effects structure.

  • Fixed variables are those which do not change over time, for example a person’s gender.
  • Random variables are those which change over time, for example a person’s weight or age.

3. Effects

Models that include both fixed and random effects are called Mixed Effects Models.

1. Fixed effects most commonly represent the experimental manipulation designed (fixed) by the researcher. We are only interested in the levels of our manipulation (i.e., conditions).

1. Random effects are those of which the experiment contains only a random sample of possible conditions. For example, because we choose a random sample of participants and items, the analysis cannot compute the effect of all types people and all types of items. Instead, it will estimate the variability attributable to our random sample of each.
*Note: unfortunately, a discussion on nested vs. crossed random effects is out of scope, but read on it here

CRUCIALLY: WE GENERALIZE THE RESULTS OF OUR FIXED EFFECTS ONTO OUR RANDOM EFFECTS AND, FROM THAT, TO THE GENERAL POPULATION.

EXAMPLE: We generalize the results of a reading experiment with actives/passives (CONDITIONS = FIXED) onto monolingual and bilingual speakers (PARTICIPANTS = RANDOM). Our study is made stronger by being able to generalize to a larger population by means of our random effects, than just being able to make an assertion about a particular group of participants if we only had fixed effects.

Covariance Structures

When creating a mixed effects model, we have to decide upon its covariance structure. In other words, will we have random intercepts and/or slopes AND which variables can be included in each.

First, we will create a model with random intercepts only. * The notation (1 | x) indicates that this is a random effect * 1| denotes it’s a random intercept * x refers to the grouping variable

CAREFUL: when we specify a covariance structure that is too simple, then we are more likely to observe a Type I error (aka false positive). More information on random effects terms in R here

model_RI <- lmer(total ~ center_congruency*center_voice # fixed effects
                                  + (1 | participant) # random intercept by participant
                                  + (1 |item) # random intercept by item
                                  , data = data
                                  , REML = TRUE
                                  , control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))
summary(model_RI)

Let’s dissect the output:

1. Goodness-of-fit

We first have a series of measures of goodness-of-fit such as AIC and BIC. By themselves, these figures don’t tell us much, but when we start building more complex models, we need to pay attention to them to see if they go down: smaller AIC values will indicate that the more complex model is accounting for more variance in the data.

2. Scaled residuals

If we plot the scaled residuals for the model, we can see the fit is good. For a correctly specified model we would expect a uniform (flat) distribution of the scaled residuals.

plot(model_RI,type=c("p","smooth"))

3. Random effects

This part of the model output is often neglected, even though it can give us important information about our model.

The standard deviation of random effects can tell us how much the intercepts varied over our participant and item variables. In this particular case, we see the standard deviations are not huge which for data set of this size. This entails there aren’t huge differences in RTs for our participant sample. This also means that we controlled for our items properly, as there aren’t huge differences in the RTs for different sentences.


4. Fixed Effects

The fixed effects indicate that:

  • There is a significant positive main effect of Congruency. For the incongruent condition, RTs go up 47.80 ms.
  • There is a significant positive main effect of Voice. For passives, RTs go up 114.78 ms
  • There is a significant positive interaction between Congruency and Voice.

Now, we will create a model that also contains random slopes:

  • The notation (1 + x | x) indicates that this is a random effect
  • 1+ denotes it’s a random slope
  • x specifies the random variables
  • denotes there is also a random intercept
  • The second x refers to the grouping variable.
model_RS <- lmer(total ~ center_congruency*center_voice # fixed effects
                                  + (1 + center_congruency+center_voice | participant) # random intercept & slope by participant
                                  + (1 + center_congruency+center_voice |item) # random intercept & slope by item
                                  , data = data
                                  , REML = TRUE
                                  , control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa"))
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')

The results are largely similar to the ones of the previous model, however, we do see that the AIC value has gone up slightly, indicating that this second model’s fit is somewhat worse. If we compare both models, we see that model with random slopes does not improve over the model random intercepts. Thus, random intercepts are enough to account for the variance in this data set.

In addition, the warning message boundary (singular) fit: see help(‘isSingular’) indicates that we are over-fitting our random effects structure. In other words, specifying a highly complicated model is not warranted in this case.

Now, the models that we have built so far are somewhat simple, we don’t have a large number of variables. In other words, these models are parsimonious, they include a conservative number of predictors. However, we could also create maximal models that include all possible predictors we are interested in, as well as their interactions. Let’s look into these possibilities:

### The debate: Maximal or Parsimonious? Barr et al. (2013) vs. Bates et al. (2018)

1. Barr et al., (2013) Random effects structure for confirmatory hypothesis testing: Keep it maximal

Key points:

  • Using maximal random-effects structures in our models can help reduce the risk of Type I error.
  • Maximal random-effects structures make findings more generalizable.

2. Bates et al., (2015) Parsimonious Mixed Models

Key points:

  • Maximal models create worrying convergence issues.
  • Maximal models can critically overfit the data.
  • Iterative reduction (i.e., stepwise selection) to create parsimonious models is preferable.


Since the advent of the study by Bates et al., few researchers use the maximal approach given its many disadvantages. In our case, if we wanted to create a larger model, we’d still need to compare it with simpler models to make sure that each predictor that we include actually improves the model’s fit. This is were stepwise regression can help us.

Stepwise regression (or stepwise selection) consists of iteratively adding and/or removing predictors in order to find the subset of variables resulting in the best performing model.

There are three strategies in stepwise regression:

  • Forward selection, which starts with no predictors in the model, iteratively adds the most contributive predictors, and stops when the improvement is no longer statistically significant.

  • Backward selection, (or backward elimination), which starts with all predictors in the model (maximal/dull model), iteratively removes the least contributive predictors, and stops when you have a model where all predictors are statistically significant.

  • Stepwise selection, (or sequential replacement), which is a combination of forward and backward selections. You start with no predictors, then sequentially add the most contributive predictors (like forward selection). After adding each new variable, remove any variables that no longer provide an improvement in the model fit (like backward selection). This tests all possible combinations aming variables.

There are several ways in which stepwise selection can be performed, here we will talk about two:

1. Manual selection: we have actually already done this above; this method consists of manually adding or subtracting a variable and then comparing models to check if the AIC values have improved (we can also use the anova function)

2. Using the function buildmer()

This function uses lmer from the lme4 package but allows for a systematic and replicable way of simplifying random effects structures and testing fixed effects. The function starts by attempting to fit the most maximal model possible. If the model fails to converge, the function then simplifies the random effects structure via backwards stepwise elimination; in other words, it attempts to find the maximal random effects structure that still allows the model to converge. Once the maximally converging model has been identified, the function calculates p-values for all fixed effects. The resulting model is the maximally converging model that the data are able to support.

First, let’s create a more “maximal” model including our known Congruency and Voice predictors, plus four more continuous proficiency measures.

Let’s dissect this output;

Formula

total ~ 1 + center_voice + PN_RT + PN_ACC + center_congruency + center_voice:center_congruency
+ (1 + center_voice | participant)
+ (1 | item)
data

We see that the final formula selected by buildmer() includes all fixed effects but VF and MELICET. In addition, it has only left a random slope for voice by participant and a random intercept by item. This entails that most of the variability in the model was captured by the predictor voice.

Other than that:

The standard deviations for the Random effects are fairly similar to those of our smaller model; we see they are still higher for participant than for item, indicating there was more variation in the former.

The Fixed effects coefficients are also largely the same:

  • A significant main effect of voice
  • A significant main effect of picture naming RTs
  • A marginally significant main effect of picture naming accuracy
  • A marginally significant main effect of information structure
  • A significant interaction between voice and information structure

In addition, we see the prompt REML criterion at convergence: 23806.2. REML stands for Restricted or residual Maximum Likelihood, this is buildmer’s default criterion to determine whether a given effect is included in the model. The model with the effect in question is compared to the corresponding model without that effect, in order to determine whether there is an increase in the goodness of the fit.
Thus, we can now provide reviewers and readers with a model that has been empirically selected and is highly reproducible, as well with a figure indicating the criterion used in the selecton.
